title: For Sale:  Mossberg model 395 KB 12 GA C-LECT-CHOKE 2 3/4--3 INch SHELL 26 or 28 IN BARREL 3 ROUND MAG Bolt-action
postcontent:
Mossberg model 395 KB, 12 GA, C-LECT-CHOKE, 2 3/4--3 INch SHELL, 26 or 28 IN BARREL with 3 ROUND (box) MAG.  Bolt-Action shotgun.

* The "C-Lect-Choke" allows one to select "Full" or "Modified" or "Improved Cylinder" by merely rotating the Choke Sleeve on the outside of the end of the barrel.

* The magazine is released from the bottom of the shotgun (for safe unloading of live rounds).  

* Comes with a rubber stock bottom /butt and installed metal sling hardware in both the front and back of the stock.

* The front sight bead was painted orange but most of the orange paint has rubbed off.

* This 12 Gauge shotgun has some rust on it.  The stock has some scrathes on it and a bit of a small chip in the wood at the top of the stock where it slopes up.

* Unfortunately somebody wanted their shotgun to look more "streamlined" so they sawed off the integral (cast) rear sight thus disrupting the line of sight for proper aiming.  To "repair" this hasty mistake they just used electrical tape to secure some bent sheet metal with a notch filed into it.   This restores the proper "line of sight" for aiming but just does not look that great.  A more professional repair could be easily done by a gunsmith or hobbyist.  This fix works well and has held up well.

* Great gun for protection in places where it may have a higher risk of getting stolen or for teaching a beginner / youngster about shotgun use.  Should it get stolen, since it did not cost all that much, it should not be as big of a deal losing it.   A youngster roughing it up in the field while hunting with an adult should also not be such a big concern given the "low purchase price".

** SALE TERMS: Would require a Face-to-Face (FTF) meeting for a cash sale.  I would need to see a VA Driver's license and a utility bill with a matching name and address on it.  also a Bill of Sale would need to be signed with a legible signature and a statement which states that you are legally allowed to own and possess a firearm (as a minimum).   (No plans on shipping it at this time).

Original owner.  Serial # 832xxx

title: For Sale:   BPCR -- Everything you need to get into the game
postcontent:
I have decided to focus my shooting efforts in the bench-rest game. With that in mind, I am making available EVERYTHING you need to get into black powder cartridge rifle (BPCR) shooting. The rifle is a Browning BPCR 1885 Highwall in 45-70 caliber. I was told by the original owner he had the trigger worked by Lee Shaver. It is smooth with a pleasant pull and breaks cleanly. Included is a Vernier rear sight and globe front sight with level. I am not sure of the round count by the original owner, but I doubt it was many as he bought it for his son who never got into the BPCR game. I have owned the rifle for three years and have fired 12 rounds. There are a few tiny marks on the cheek-piece and one near the butt plat at the top of the comb. There is one tiny blemish on the barrel. I tried to capture these flaws in photos. They are essentially unnoticeable unless you are looking closely for them. I have the original rifle box. title: For Sale:  BSA commonwealth of Australia model #6
postcontent: Models 6 & 13 are essentially light sporting/target rifles. Weight is about 6 - 7 lbs. and the lightest we have found. These have a barrel about 25" long, 7/8" diameter at the breech, and a pencil taper to 5/8" at the muzzle. Actions may be thinwall (like the Cadet), thickwall, or rebated (thickwall at breech, thinwall at stock). Straight grip stock with a lightweight forend. A few are found with the take-down feature, and a few are seen in .300 Rook centerfire. They come with either a target style rear peep sight (Parker-Hale 7 or 7A), or a barrel mounted open 'v' or ladder sight. Very few are found. They appear to have been manufactured between 1909 and 1939. Serial numbers are mixed with other models and are found in the 9,000 to the high 59,000 range. A few were made with an "R" prefix in the R10,000 - R13,000 serial range. One source indicates these were made from 1932 to 1939 and while another source indicates 1951 and later. Note: Some barrels may be relined.
